ùíŸ@525fa7bb7a8f09dc7058e00a69f2bf6415f5a114cd70dff65309f43d321b9d70⁄˝Title: Hooks
Path: Hooks
Content:
Hooks allow you to run a code snippet at some predefined situations.

They are only available in the interactive mode (
[link: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Read%E2%80%93eval%E2%80%93print_loop] REPL
), they do not work if you run Nushell with a script (
``nu script.nu``
) or command (
``nu -c "print foo"``
) argument.
Currently, we support these types of hooks:
``pre_prompt``
 : Triggered before the prompt is drawn
``pre_execution``
 : Triggered before the line input starts executing
``env_change``
 : Triggered when an environment variable changes
``display_output``
 : A block that the output is passed to
``command_not_found``
 : Triggered when a command is not found
To make it clearer, we can break down Nushell's execution cycle.

The steps to evaluate one line in the REPL mode are as follows:
Check for 
``pre_prompt``
 hooks and run them
Check for 
``env_change``
 hooks and run them
Display prompt and wait for user input
After user typed something and pressed "Enter": Check for 
``pre_execution``
 hooks and run them
Parse and evaluate user input
If a command is not found: Run the 
``command_not_found``
 hook. If it returns a string, show it.
If 
``display_output``
 is defined, use it to print command output
Return to 1.
íŸ@e676ad4ca26023895d15477166c09b6edacd49d19cee717329c8e12f1190aaad⁄œTitle: Hooks
Path: Basic Hooks
Content:
To enable hooks, define them in your 
[link: configuration.md] config
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config.hooks = {
    pre_prompt: [{ print "pre prompt hook" }]
    pre_execution: [{ print "pre exec hook" }]
    env_change: {
        PWD: [{|before, after| print $"changing directory from ($before) to ($after)" }]
    }
}

```
Try putting the above into your config, running Nushell and moving around your filesystem.

When you change a directory, the 
``PWD``
 environment variable changes and the change triggers the hook with the previous and the current values stored in 
``before``
 and 
``after``
 variables, respectively.
Instead of defining just a single hook per trigger, it is possible to define a 
list of hooks
 which will run in sequence:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config.hooks = {
    pre_prompt: [
        { print "pre prompt hook" }
        { print "pre prompt hook2" }
    ]
    pre_execution: [
        { print "pre exec hook" }
        { print "pre exec hook2" }
    ]
    env_change: {
        PWD: [
            {|before, after| print $"changing directory from ($before) to ($after)" }
            {|before, after| print $"changing directory from ($before) to ($after) 2" }
        ]
    }
}

```
Instead of replacing all hooks, you can append a new hook to existing configuration:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config.hooks.pre_execution = $env.config.hooks.pre_execution | append { print "pre exec hook3" }

```
íŸ@96e6f0c73622c6a3f276fda84a8637c347cfe634fa0e721fd06f99bce526f786⁄sTitle: Hooks
Path: Changing Environment
Content:
One feature of the hooks is that they preserve the environment.

Environment variables defined inside the hook 
block
 will be preserved in a similar way as 
[link: environment.md#defining-environment-from-custom-commands] ``def --env``
.

You can test it with the following example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config = ($env.config | upsert hooks {
    pre_prompt: { $env.SPAM = "eggs" }
})

$env.SPAM
# => eggs

```
The hook blocks otherwise follow the general scoping rules, i.e., commands, aliases, etc. defined within the block will be thrown away once the block ends.
íŸ@23101037cfb1a7be399a2ab514552f2702a7a4207bec71edf335bc728569beb6⁄˜Title: Hooks
Path:  Hooks
Content:
``pre_execution``
``pre_execution``
 hooks can inspect the to-be-executed command through the 
[link: /commands/docs/commandline.md] ``commandline``
 command
.
For example, to print the command being executed:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config = (
    $env.config
    | upsert hooks.pre_execution [ {||
        $env.repl_commandline = (commandline)
        print $"Command: ($env.repl_commandline)"
    } ]
)

print (1 + 3)
# => Command: print (1 + 3)
# => 4

```
íŸ@a9fdf840441e7ae17e0f3783151630b5d35d8d21e6949ecd47ecaeda33b66f89⁄bTitle: Hooks
Path: Conditional Hooks
Content:
One thing you might be tempted to do is to activate an environment whenever you enter a directory:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config = ($env.config | upsert hooks {
    env_change: {
        PWD: [
            {|before, after|
                if $after == /some/path/to/directory {
                    load-env { SPAM: eggs }
                }
            }
        ]
    }
})

```
This won't work because the environment will be active only within the 
[link: /commands/docs/if.md] ``if``
 block.

In this case, you could easily rewrite it as 
``load-env (if $after == ... { ... } else { {} })``
 but this pattern is fairly common and later we'll see that not all cases can be rewritten like this.
To deal with the above problem, we introduce another way to define a hook - 
a record
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config = ($env.config | upsert hooks {
    env_change: {
        PWD: [
            {
                condition: {|before, after| $after == /some/path/to/directory }
                code: {|before, after| load-env { SPAM: eggs } }
            }
        ]
    }
})

```
When the hook triggers, it evaluates the 
``condition``
 block.

If it returns 
``true``
, the 
``code``
 block will be evaluated.

If it returns 
``false``
, nothing will happen.

If it returns something else, an error will be thrown.

The 
``condition``
 field can also be omitted altogether in which case the hook will always evaluate.
The 
``pre_prompt``
 and 
``pre_execution``
 hook types also support the conditional hooks but they don't accept the 
``before``
 and 
``after``
 parameters.
íŸ@74bb04e58ad8e1200472419fafe28f9602adbda1f6b5a1a561a9e004934a6791⁄üTitle: Hooks
Path: Hooks as Strings
Content:
So far a hook was defined as a block that preserves only the environment, but nothing else.

To be able to define commands or aliases, it is possible to define the 
``code``
 field as 
a string
.

You can think of it as if you typed the string into the REPL and hit Enter.

So, the hook from the previous section can be also written as
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config = ($env.config | upsert hooks {
    pre_prompt: '$env.SPAM = "eggs"'
})

$env.SPAM
# => eggs

```
This feature can be used, for example, to conditionally bring in definitions based on the current directory:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config = ($env.config | upsert hooks {
    env_change: {
        PWD: [
            {
                condition: {|_, after| $after == /some/path/to/directory }
                code: 'def foo [] { print "foo" }'
            }
            {
                condition: {|before, _| $before == /some/path/to/directory }
                code: 'hide foo'
            }
        ]
    }
})

```
When defining a hook as a string, the 
``$before``
 and 
``$after``
 variables are set to the previous and current environment variable value, respectively, similarly to the previous examples:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config = ($env.config | upsert hooks {
    env_change: {
        PWD: {
            code: 'print $"changing directory from ($before) to ($after)"'
        }
    }
}

```
íŸ@c52548b66c1146c97612ba0d01525f0b462a4af969f74f153c5ba3bae5266d84⁄˜Title: Hooks
Path: Adding a Single Hook to Existing Config
Content:
An example for PWD env change hook:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config = ($env.config | upsert hooks.env_change.PWD {|config|
    let val = ($config | get -o hooks.env_change.PWD)

    if $val == null {
        $val | append {|before, after| print $"changing directory from ($before) to ($after)" }
    } else {
        [
            {|before, after| print $"changing directory from ($before) to ($after)" }
        ]
    }
})

```
íŸ@024718c9afac61a2d8b3f810b612750c559604c07217472612afc34583ba4221⁄Title: Hooks
Path: Automatically Activating an Environment when Entering a Directory
Content:
This one looks for 
``test-env.nu``
 in a directory
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config = ($env.config | upsert hooks.env_change.PWD {
    [
        {
            condition: {|_, after|
                ($after == '/path/to/target/dir'
                    and ($after | path join test-env.nu | path exists))
            }
            code: "overlay use test-env.nu"
        }
        {
            condition: {|before, after|
                ('/path/to/target/dir' not-in $after
                    and '/path/to/target/dir' in ($before | default "")
                    and 'test-env' in (overlay list))
            }
            code: "overlay hide test-env --keep-env [ PWD ]"
        }
    ]
})

```
íŸ@09cdbc4151b06b4897de03368c064c9ee9ecbe6f92529e221a6329f01c48c8aa⁄ñTitle: Hooks
Path: Filtering or Diverting Command Output
Content:
You can use the 
``display_output``
 hook to redirect the output of commands.

You should define a block that works on all value types.

The output of external commands is not filtered through 
``display_output``
.
This hook can display the output in a separate window,

perhaps as rich HTML text. Here is the basic idea of how to do that:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config = ($env.config | upsert hooks {
    display_output: { to html --partial --no-color | save --raw /tmp/nu-output.html }
})

```
You can view the result by opening 
``file:///tmp/nu-output.html``
 in

a web browser.

Of course this isn't very convenient unless you use

a browser that automatically reloads when the file changes.

Instead of the 
[link: /commands/docs/save.md] ``save``
 command, you would normally customize this

to send the HTML output to a desired window.
íŸ@5942ca621887324ac86978624a1ad64be57070b4b6be7c82f941e37a90bc8619⁄÷Title: Hooks
Path: Changing how Output is Displayed
Content:
You can change to default behavior of how output is displayed by using the 
``display_output``
 hook.

Here is an example that changes the default display behavior to show a table 1 layer deep if the terminal is wide enough, or collapse otherwise:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config = ($env.config | upsert hooks {
    display_output: {if (term size).columns >= 100 { table -ed 1 } else { table }}
})

```
íŸ@8e610027bf2b5db21f6a7c3542dde485ee00697d1ad4af2c890011cc1086d55d⁄"Title: Hooks
Path: Arch Linux
Content:
``command_not_found``
The following hook uses the 
``pkgfile``
 command, to find which packages commands belong to in 
Arch Linux
.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config = {
    ...other config...

    hooks: {
        ...other hooks...

        command_not_found: {
            |cmd_name| (
                try {
                    let pkgs = (pkgfile --binaries --verbose $cmd_name)
                    if ($pkgs | is-empty) {
                        return null
                    }
                    (
                        $"(ansi $env.config.color_config.shape_external)($cmd_name)(ansi reset) " +
                        $"may be found in the following packages:\n($pkgs)"
                    )
                }
            )
        }
    }
}

```
íŸ@fad1a0c718ebbbb7662270600311b0160c35e40f190c58f4800e497641092488⁄*Title: Hooks
Path: NixOS
Content:
``command_not_found``
NixOS comes with the command 
``command-not-found``
. We only need to plug it in the nushell hook:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config.hooks.command_not_found = {
  |command_name|
  print (command-not-found $command_name | str trim)
}

```
íŸ@c6f7893c0a9203e985b2146c9fae0e8166d13b6bfc04c9209e026f4775229c1f⁄?Title: Hooks
Path: Windows
Content:
``command_not_found``
The following hook uses the 
``ftype``
 command, to find program paths in 
Windows
 that might be relevant to the user for 
``alias``
-ing.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
$env.config = {
    ...other config...

    hooks: {
        ...other hooks...

        command_not_found: {
            |cmd_name| (
                try {
                    let attrs = (
                        ftype | find $cmd_name | to text | lines | reduce -f [] { |line, acc|
                            $line | parse "{type}={path}" | append $acc
                        } | group-by path | transpose key value | each { |row|
                            { path: $row.key, types: ($row.value | get type | str join ", ") }
                        }
                    )
                    let len = ($attrs | length)

                    if $len == 0 {
                        return null
                    } else {
                        return ($attrs | table --collapse)
                    }
                }
            )
        }
    }
}

```
